1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:29,980
 So good afternoon ladies and gentlemen excellencies first of all let me thank you very much the organizers and in particular we have Poland for this very very nice invitation to talk come here to talk about innovation new solutions i know that you are economists and our technologies but i think we very well

2
00:00:29,980 --> 00:00:59,960
 complement and also let me say that the two sessions that we had already here which touched on the green transition technologies were very professional i tried to really continue from that that where we left my talk today is is really more on technologies and i i tried to show show you some of the solutions which actually are there this is state of the art but also try to show you what's behind the corner because the future looks much brighter than you might look think in terms of innovation

3
00:00:59,960 --> 00:01:21,960
 and in terms of technologies there's a range of new technologies coming over certain timeline which are very promising and maybe of course part of the solution on carbon decarbonization i will also touch about some of the mechanism that we need to push these new technologies forward

4
00:01:21,960 --> 00:01:25,440
 But I will start with the big frame.

5
00:01:25,440 --> 00:01:30,360
 Let's frame the question about technologies in terms of the challenges that we have.

6
00:01:30,360 --> 00:01:35,480
 I think when the historians, after some few centuries, define this century,

7
00:01:35,480 --> 00:01:39,380
 they will define it as a century of climate change and sustainability.

8
00:01:39,380 --> 00:01:43,660
 This is the century of climate change and definitely sustainability.

9
00:01:43,660 --> 00:01:49,260
 And the whole century will, in some way, be characterized by these themes.

10
00:01:50,020 --> 00:01:54,720
 It's important also to recognize that climate change, climate action,

11
00:01:54,720 --> 00:01:57,620
 is part of the larger sustainable development goals.

12
00:01:57,620 --> 00:01:59,800
 And let's not forget those as well.

13
00:01:59,800 --> 00:02:02,220
 There's poverty, education, water, etc.

14
00:02:02,220 --> 00:02:05,880
 Climate change is for sure linked to many of those.

15
00:02:05,880 --> 00:02:09,940
 But in terms of policies, we should keep in mind this broader picture.

16
00:02:09,940 --> 00:02:16,920
 So the SDG, 17 goals, let's keep those in mind when we go further with the new technologies.

17
00:02:18,080 --> 00:02:21,780
 The challenge that we have in front of us is shown here.

18
00:02:21,780 --> 00:02:32,440
 The emissions, if we would not do anything, as the Georgieva, IAMFBOS, showed us,

19
00:02:32,440 --> 00:02:35,200
 will lead us to a catastrophe.

20
00:02:35,200 --> 00:02:44,920
 So the up-going curve, indeed, will cause ecosystem damages from which the planet most likely will not recover.

21
00:02:45,880 --> 00:02:51,980
 The Paris goals are clear, where to go in order to reach sustainability by 2050, 2060.

22
00:02:51,980 --> 00:02:57,300
 Middle of the century, the emissions should be imbalanced with the sinks.

23
00:02:57,300 --> 00:03:02,220
 So we should be at a so-called carbon neutrality level, as you sure know.

24
00:03:02,220 --> 00:03:06,200
 Now the challenge is that the emissions have not come down.

25
00:03:06,340 --> 00:03:12,680
 The challenges are maybe leveling out, but the emissions increase with the economy.

26
00:03:12,680 --> 00:03:15,940
 So we have economic growth, the emissions increase.

27
00:03:15,940 --> 00:03:20,880
 And the reason is very simple, because most of the energy, 80% of the energy, is still fossil fuel-based.

28
00:03:20,880 --> 00:03:24,200
 And it has been for the last 20 years or so.

29
00:03:24,700 --> 00:03:27,200
 So we haven't seen any radical change in that.

30
00:03:27,200 --> 00:03:32,660
 And now there's a big question, when would the emissions globally start to come down?

31
00:03:32,660 --> 00:03:42,520
 If we want to keep on the pace of the Paris Climate Agreement, the emissions should reduce by the end of this decade by 40%.

32
00:03:42,520 --> 00:03:48,480
 40% globally is a huge challenge, but that is the path that we have to take.

33
00:03:48,480 --> 00:03:53,740
 And then, as said, by 2050, 2060, we would reach then carbon neutrality.

34
00:03:53,740 --> 00:04:01,340
 This is perhaps the largest quest that mankind have ever had, and indeed should be taken very seriously.

35
00:04:03,620 --> 00:04:07,900
 There's many effects, of course, from the climate change and climate change mitigation.

36
00:04:07,900 --> 00:04:16,280
 Economic effects will be, of course, a major investment, 2% to 3% of the GDP.

37
00:04:16,280 --> 00:04:21,600
 So you can understand much of the economic growth may go into the investment for the future.

38
00:04:21,600 --> 00:04:27,400
 But also, there will be stranded assets from the fossil fuels, which will not be used.

39
00:04:27,400 --> 00:04:33,240
 80% of coal would need to remain unused, 30%, 40% of the gas and oil.

40
00:04:33,620 --> 00:04:36,560
 And that's definitely a major political question as well.

41
00:04:36,560 --> 00:04:39,140
 So not a simple question globally.

42
00:04:39,140 --> 00:04:47,220
 The culprit for going to carbon neutrality is clear.

43
00:04:47,220 --> 00:04:52,100
 Even though we have problems in order to do that, but it's clear what to do.

44
00:04:52,100 --> 00:04:58,020
 And the International Energy Agency just recently issued the last plan,

45
00:04:58,020 --> 00:05:01,160
 how to reach carbon neutrality by 2050.

46
00:05:01,780 --> 00:05:03,560
 There's four major pillars in that.

47
00:05:03,560 --> 00:05:05,260
 The first is that the energy system.

48
00:05:05,260 --> 00:05:10,940
 The energy system constitutes about 60% of all the greenhouse gas emissions.

49
00:05:10,940 --> 00:05:13,420
 So we need to do something with the energy systems.

50
00:05:13,420 --> 00:05:19,340
 Those have to be net emission-based by 2050.

51
00:05:19,340 --> 00:05:20,540
 That is carbon neutral.

52
00:05:21,540 --> 00:05:24,840
 And you see here on the right-hand side also how to do that.

53
00:05:24,840 --> 00:05:27,160
 Clean electricity will be very important.

54
00:05:27,160 --> 00:05:33,980
 All in all, electricity of the final energy uses will be the most important.

55
00:05:33,980 --> 00:05:39,360
 The electricity use, as we have heard before, will increase quite much by the middle of the century.

56
00:05:39,360 --> 00:05:41,240
 At least doubling, maybe tripling.

57
00:05:42,280 --> 00:05:48,400
 Also, we have to change the fuels from the present fuels into alternative fuels, clean fuels, and to electrification.

58
00:05:48,400 --> 00:05:51,280
 So e-mobility will be extremely important.

59
00:05:51,280 --> 00:05:55,400
 Those are clear messages.

60
00:05:55,400 --> 00:05:57,420
 And there's a lot of technologies to do that.

61
00:05:58,180 --> 00:06:02,520
 But in addition to that, we need to look on other things like also other greenhouse gas emissions.

62
00:06:02,520 --> 00:06:05,540
 Now we're focusing very often on CO2, which is important.

63
00:06:05,540 --> 00:06:11,860
 But we have forgotten that 30%, 30% of the greenhouse emissions are methane emissions.

64
00:06:11,860 --> 00:06:17,980
 So methane leakages and how we cultivate our agriculture in the future may be important.

65
00:06:17,980 --> 00:06:24,380
 You will see now that actually climate change mitigation goes also to other sectors, not just the energy sector.

66
00:06:25,380 --> 00:06:31,340
 But maybe the most important to remaining one's pillars are, first of all, energy efficiency.

67
00:06:31,340 --> 00:06:36,300
 Or let's say efficient use of energy, in the sense that you get more with less.

68
00:06:36,300 --> 00:06:38,120
 I think economists must like that.

69
00:06:38,120 --> 00:06:39,240
 You get more with less.

70
00:06:39,240 --> 00:06:42,700
 But that is for energy, is really the key point.

71
00:06:42,700 --> 00:06:49,880
 IEA estimates that about 40% of all emissions reductions come from energy efficiency.

72
00:06:49,880 --> 00:06:54,280
 Energy efficiency, energy savings, as EU say, comes first.

73
00:06:54,280 --> 00:06:56,980
 Then you can start to think about supply options.

74
00:06:56,980 --> 00:07:01,880
 So the saved energy is much more precious than the suspended energy.

75
00:07:01,880 --> 00:07:06,520
 Now having done all these tricks, the question is, would that be enough?

76
00:07:06,520 --> 00:07:11,380
 Unfortunately not, anymore, as emissions are not coming down yet.

77
00:07:11,380 --> 00:07:13,640
 And we would need carbon management.

78
00:07:13,640 --> 00:07:19,500
 So we have to remove carbon from the atmosphere or from our fossil fuel plants and store that underground.

79
00:07:19,960 --> 00:07:26,420
 Carbon management becomes increasingly important the more we go closer to 2040, 2050.

80
00:07:26,420 --> 00:07:29,740
 And that's something to start to anticipate about.

81
00:07:29,740 --> 00:07:40,440
 So indeed, this is the major blueprint for how to reduce emissions to the Paris Agreement goals.

82
00:07:42,100 --> 00:07:48,880
 You may imagine that all the sectors of the society will be affected by climate change mitigation.

83
00:07:48,880 --> 00:07:51,520
 And it doesn't leave anybody cold, so to say.

84
00:07:51,520 --> 00:08:00,800
 And that's why I think it may be better also to characterize the energy transition as more as a societal transition, like the Industrial Revolution.

85
00:08:01,660 --> 00:08:08,560
 And indeed, when we think about the measures, we know technologies, I focus on those today.

86
00:08:08,560 --> 00:08:17,840
 But let's not forget that the societal impacts and also the social impacts are very important, not to speak about the economic impacts.

87
00:08:18,220 --> 00:08:22,240
 So we could think about the transition more as a clockwork, which has gears.

88
00:08:22,240 --> 00:08:27,620
 And all the gears have to move in a synchronous way that the clock goes forward.

89
00:08:27,620 --> 00:08:35,140
 If, for instance, most of the population resists the transition, you don't have acceptance, it stops.

90
00:08:35,140 --> 00:08:35,980
 You can't do anything.

91
00:08:35,980 --> 00:08:39,940
 So the social issues, as we heard in the last panel, will be more important.

92
00:08:39,940 --> 00:08:43,580
 Just socially just transition is important.

93
00:08:43,740 --> 00:08:49,460
 So very often, any transition links may be your mind to changing your technology or another one.

94
00:08:49,460 --> 00:08:51,460
 It's not enough.

95
00:08:51,460 --> 00:08:55,320
 You have to look on the whole picture on a societal change.

96
00:08:55,320 --> 00:08:59,020
 And that makes the whole transition even more complicated.

97
00:08:59,020 --> 00:09:08,220
 The European Academies here some time ago, when giving advice to the commissioners, pointed out that, yes, this is a systemic change.

98
00:09:08,220 --> 00:09:09,920
 So you need to look on the whole picture.

99
00:09:10,920 --> 00:09:15,720
 Questions like the carbon pricing, as we heard from the mention director of IMF.

100
00:09:15,720 --> 00:09:24,300
 Carbon pricing is one of the most important, actually, measures, which leading climate economies of Europe advise.

101
00:09:24,300 --> 00:09:34,860
 Also, certain technology diversity will be necessary, as we will see later, in the sense that all countries in Europe, at least, are very heterogeneous.

102
00:09:34,860 --> 00:09:39,220
 You have different backgrounds, and one solution may not fit all countries.

103
00:09:39,220 --> 00:09:46,440
 So technology diversity, climate pricing may be key issues that we need also to keep in mind in this talk.

104
00:09:48,180 --> 00:09:54,900
 So where do Europe stand in terms of climate change mitigation, and I'm also taking into the picture the energy security?

105
00:09:54,900 --> 00:09:59,260
 Well, we have done much, but there's still very much to be done.

106
00:09:59,260 --> 00:10:07,540
 Let's not forget that around 70% of all energy in Europe is still fossil fuel.

107
00:10:08,100 --> 00:10:14,940
 Remember globally, it's 80%, 70%, all the red colors here are fossil fuels.

108
00:10:14,940 --> 00:10:23,980
 And just before the crisis, energy crisis, 60% of our energy was important, the highest of any continent.

109
00:10:24,780 --> 00:10:27,740
 U.S. is energy independent, basically.

110
00:10:27,740 --> 00:10:30,040
 China, also almost.

111
00:10:30,040 --> 00:10:33,460
 And that energy dependency caused the energy crisis.

112
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:42,300
 So we have shoved ourselves in our foot that we didn't actually take seriously energy security 10, 20 years ago, when the first signals came there.

113
00:10:42,300 --> 00:10:50,260
 And now when we speak about climate change mitigation, of course, we have to look on both issues.

114
00:10:50,260 --> 00:10:57,220
 Unfortunately, the measures, being energy efficiency or clean energy solutions, work in the direction that security improves and the emissions reduce.

115
00:10:57,220 --> 00:11:15,580
 So, of course, the EU programs now, the updated programs, the Green Deal with the EU power and Fit for 55, and so on programs, are very important now in the context to really divert Europe from the fossil fuel path to the clean power path.

116
00:11:15,580 --> 00:11:20,740
 By the end, you see that the challenges are huge.

117
00:11:21,740 --> 00:11:28,220
 It's also important to point out that the member states that we have in Europe don't stand at the same standing point.

118
00:11:28,220 --> 00:11:35,360
 So, if you think about the climate change mitigation as a marathon, some of the countries are 10 kilometers off before the race are starting.

119
00:11:35,360 --> 00:11:51,200
 And the reason is that, of course, if you look on the carbon intensity of the countries here, which is shown by the blue color, or on the wealth of the countries shown by green, they differ very much among European countries.

120
00:11:51,740 --> 00:12:05,440
 Very often, Northern countries, or those countries with hydropower or with large bioenergy resources, or a century ago, actually started to use those, and they didn't know anything about climate change.

121
00:12:05,440 --> 00:12:13,420
 I think about century European countries, their indigenous resource in energy was fossil fuel, very often coal, and they used that.

122
00:12:13,920 --> 00:12:25,780
 Now, when we start to reduce emissions, you can imagine those countries who had bioenergy or hydropower by chance, they are well off already in climate change mitigation without doing anything.

123
00:12:26,520 --> 00:12:35,840
 So, those countries on the left-hand side, they have to do much more than those countries on the right-hand side of the picture.

124
00:12:35,840 --> 00:12:47,200
 And you can imagine that we need climate solidarity within Europe in order, in some way, to be able to incorporate the different measures and technologies to reduce emissions.

125
00:12:49,200 --> 00:12:55,520
 This is, of course, a major political question, and I think, for sure, also a very important question.

126
00:12:55,520 --> 00:12:58,120
 Can we succeed with the climate change mitigation?

127
00:12:58,120 --> 00:13:07,900
 Now, there comes the question, where is the globe going with the investments in terms of reducing carbon emissions?

128
00:13:07,900 --> 00:13:11,800
 We know that the carbon emissions, they are leveling out.

129
00:13:11,940 --> 00:13:14,380
 We don't yet know when they started to run down.

130
00:13:14,380 --> 00:13:15,740
 They should do it already.

131
00:13:15,740 --> 00:13:18,820
 And these are, these are bad news.

132
00:13:18,820 --> 00:13:24,740
 But the good news, very good news, is that the markets have changed very much.

133
00:13:24,740 --> 00:13:34,380
 Actually, last year, if you look at all energy investments globally, the majority of all investments went to clean energy.

134
00:13:34,380 --> 00:13:38,380
 Renewables surpassed the investments in fossil fuels.

135
00:13:39,180 --> 00:13:42,300
 60% of all investments goes now to clean energy.

136
00:13:42,300 --> 00:13:48,920
 And that's important to recognize, of course, that we can't change what we did in the past, but we can change now the future by doing now.

137
00:13:48,920 --> 00:14:07,280
 And that's why these investments that are increasing, you see the green columns with renewables, they are increasing, energy efficiency increasing, grid investments increasing, a very important infrastructure investment to enable use of renewables or any clean power technologies.

138
00:14:07,600 --> 00:14:13,840
 All those are increasing, so all together, this would be a very, very positive signal.

139
00:14:13,840 --> 00:14:21,900
 Energy crisis and the COVID-19 aftermath have also increased investments, in particular in Europe.

140
00:14:21,900 --> 00:14:26,320
 Last year, 30 to 50% increase in renewable energy investments.

141
00:14:26,460 --> 00:14:30,000
 And that will continue, most likely this year, energy efficiency improving.

142
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:39,820
 So, this big crisis that we have had here around last year have, in some way, perhaps, changed the pace also to introduce better the new technologies.

143
00:14:42,620 --> 00:15:04,940
 Importantly, to emphasize, is also that, well, we put certain percentage of a GNP into change, but I am a believer of the Schubertian creative destruction, in the sense that now when we destruct those fossil fuel industries, the clean energy will actually create more new industries, and the numbers support that.

144
00:15:04,940 --> 00:15:16,300
 We have already, we have already close to 30 million jobs in renewable energy only, and I'm not accounting for energy storage or energy efficiency, which is millions on the top of that.

145
00:15:16,300 --> 00:15:21,720
 And we start to be in a point where we have more working places in clean energy than in the fossil fuel energy.

146
00:15:22,400 --> 00:15:31,060
 So, it means that this transition will also create jobs and welfare, which is extremely important for the societal impact and also for the economy.

147
00:15:31,060 --> 00:15:41,920
 And here, we see also for the different technologies, how those jobs are now split, solar energy, wind energy, for instance, quite important.

148
00:15:41,920 --> 00:15:50,080
 Now, you may ask yourself, why are we investing already so much in renewables and new technologies?

149
00:15:51,260 --> 00:15:55,200
 Are there maybe subsidies so much that it spurs these investments?

150
00:15:55,200 --> 00:16:03,080
 And the question is, actually, it's now the market mechanisms that take care of the growth of the new technologies.

151
00:16:03,080 --> 00:16:13,680
 In this figure, you see different recent statistics on the price of electricity produced by different technologies.

152
00:16:14,500 --> 00:16:27,520
 And in most of the figures that we have nowadays, shows that wind and solar, as an example, the newest technologies, are actually already competitive by based on the price of electricity that they produce.

153
00:16:27,520 --> 00:16:37,120
 On the, particularly on the right-hand side, you see with the latest numbers, which show that solar wind would be cheaper than fossil fuel electricity production.

154
00:16:37,380 --> 00:16:45,380
 So then question is, is that, well, should I invest to dirty, more expensive energy, or clean, cheaper energy?

155
00:16:45,380 --> 00:16:50,120
 And I think the markets make a correct conclusion.

156
00:16:50,120 --> 00:16:52,680
 We invest more into clean and cheaper energy.

157
00:16:54,260 --> 00:17:07,540
 If this development goes on, and let's just look on the right-hand figure here, let's assume that things go well, and the prices are at the level that we have here.

158
00:17:08,200 --> 00:17:20,540
 International Energy Agency estimates that by 2050, a critical year for carbon neutrality, up to 70% of all electricity globally would be solar and wind.

159
00:17:20,540 --> 00:17:29,220
 And you see here a clear change away from the fossil fuel production into renewable production.

160
00:17:29,220 --> 00:17:36,580
 We will need, of course, other technologies as well, but these are one of the mainstream lines that we have here.

161
00:17:37,120 --> 00:17:43,660
 Also, technologies like hydrogen are starting to appear in the scenarios by 2050.

162
00:17:43,660 --> 00:17:53,960
 Hydrogen, an important, well, energy storage by a fuel, which we can use, make by electricity, and energy efficiency, definitely also part of that.

163
00:17:53,960 --> 00:17:56,300
 And also CCS comes there already.

164
00:17:56,300 --> 00:17:58,840
 So it's like a fruit salad.

165
00:17:58,840 --> 00:18:03,680
 You have a range of technologies, and this, of course, caused some challenges.

166
00:18:05,980 --> 00:18:11,320
 As you know, solar and wind are weather-based, weather-based technologies.

167
00:18:11,320 --> 00:18:12,360
 It's not a fuel.

168
00:18:12,360 --> 00:18:18,440
 And our question is that if we have so much wind and solar, have IEA made some mistake?

169
00:18:18,440 --> 00:18:24,020
 Because, I mean, we have to live also in the night when there's no solar, and also live when there's no wind.

170
00:18:24,760 --> 00:18:36,720
 And here comes a very important point later on here, is that actually, in addition to wind and solar, we have also to look on flexibility, infrastructures.

171
00:18:36,720 --> 00:18:39,520
 So fuel, that is very good.

172
00:18:39,520 --> 00:18:42,500
 You can regulate your power system based on demand.

173
00:18:43,100 --> 00:18:44,260
 With weather, you can't do it.

174
00:18:44,260 --> 00:18:50,900
 But if you add flexibility to weather, so weather plus flexibility start to be like a fuel in the power system.

175
00:18:50,900 --> 00:18:57,360
 Now, before going more into technical details, let's take something that may be important for the audience.

176
00:18:57,360 --> 00:18:58,920
 You are economists here.

177
00:18:58,920 --> 00:19:05,240
 And let me just take a few slides also and comments on the market acceleration, which is necessary.

178
00:19:05,700 --> 00:19:06,860
 Even the numbers look very good.

179
00:19:06,860 --> 00:19:08,120
 These are very promising numbers.

180
00:19:08,120 --> 00:19:13,780
 We need to easily triple, quadruple the amount of new technologies on the market.

181
00:19:13,780 --> 00:19:18,020
 So very good signals and market news are not enough.

182
00:19:18,020 --> 00:19:21,240
 And we need, indeed, to accelerate.

183
00:19:21,240 --> 00:19:23,860
 Market signals, that's what we need.

184
00:19:23,860 --> 00:19:27,600
 In some of the technologies which aren't there, we don't have market signals enough.

185
00:19:27,600 --> 00:19:30,640
 For instance, for flexibility, energy storage.

186
00:19:30,640 --> 00:19:35,400
 There's no market signals for energy storage, even though we know that, well, we will need that.

187
00:19:35,700 --> 00:19:39,960
 And in that sense, the policymaker should be more alert on that.

188
00:19:39,960 --> 00:19:45,220
 And thinking about the energy transition and technologies, how to speed now.

189
00:19:45,220 --> 00:19:48,480
 Now, you have, I'm simplifying very much.

190
00:19:48,480 --> 00:19:51,260
 You have two types of measures which you can use.

191
00:19:51,260 --> 00:19:55,500
 You have the technology push, which is R&D, development, piloting.

192
00:19:55,500 --> 00:20:04,760
 And then you have the market pull, which are, for instance, I would not call subsidies, but let's say learning investments.

193
00:20:05,120 --> 00:20:10,800
 You really pull the market with some kind of support.

194
00:20:10,800 --> 00:20:18,940
 If you've been successful in combining market pull and technology push, you come to a positive vicious circle.

195
00:20:18,940 --> 00:20:26,740
 Where the price comes down, increase the market, which again decreases the price, which gives you, again, new energy markets.

196
00:20:27,240 --> 00:20:29,900
 And that, since happens, a major global penetration.

197
00:20:29,900 --> 00:20:31,920
 We've seen this with batteries.

198
00:20:31,920 --> 00:20:33,660
 We've seen that with photovoltaics.

199
00:20:33,660 --> 00:20:42,260
 That the clever use of this mechanism can be very efficient economically and lead to major market penetration.

200
00:20:42,260 --> 00:20:48,840
 And indeed, when we speak about the global energy system change, you have to think really about the economic efficiency.

201
00:20:48,920 --> 00:20:58,920
 I think the price of the energy that these technologies produce is a very important factor to think about when we look on investments because of the huge magnitude of investment.

202
00:20:59,560 --> 00:21:07,700
 We speak about trillions now instead of billions when we look on the energy change, technology change globally.

203
00:21:07,700 --> 00:21:12,440
 Funding energy R&D.

204
00:21:13,240 --> 00:21:20,320
 Well, when I speak of technologies, that is important in the sense that the technology push activities are still very important.

205
00:21:20,320 --> 00:21:22,980
 You have to do some improvements in technologies.

206
00:21:22,980 --> 00:21:26,400
 And indeed, that requires some R&D funding.

207
00:21:27,660 --> 00:21:36,240
 We have, of course, public funding on R&D, but even more importantly, which has been forgotten, is, of course, the corporate R&D funding.

208
00:21:36,240 --> 00:21:40,200
 Corporate R&D funding is about three times higher than the public funding.

209
00:21:40,200 --> 00:21:51,860
 If we take the European funding on public funding on R&D, that's the bottom line, bottom figure here, shows that we put most of our funding in energy efficiency.

210
00:21:52,780 --> 00:21:57,300
 Then comes nuclear, and then slightly less on renewables.

211
00:21:57,300 --> 00:22:04,300
 That's how we invest in Europe, our R&D funding, and it's on long-term, on long-term, of course, R&D.

212
00:22:04,300 --> 00:22:13,820
 And the corporate funding goes to more short-term, very important technology development, which you need to do in order to bridge the technology and the market.

213
00:22:14,420 --> 00:22:22,660
 And that's very surprising there, that most of the funding goes actually, or the corporate funds, goes to mobility, electric vehicles, and batteries.

214
00:22:22,660 --> 00:22:27,880
 That's the bulk of the investment, and less on the supply side, which is surprising.

215
00:22:27,880 --> 00:22:35,240
 I mean, we're talking about energy, but still, the energy supply side gets much less than the automotive side.

216
00:22:35,340 --> 00:22:46,120
 So, thinking about now, the large energy transition, most likely we should have a lot of solutions coming up, or European solutions coming up, also on the transport sector.

217
00:22:46,120 --> 00:22:59,560
 Globally looking on these investments, it's a pity that these emerging economies, emerging economies, they invest very little in R&D.

218
00:22:59,900 --> 00:23:03,240
 Even though we know that more than half of all investments have to take place there.

219
00:23:03,240 --> 00:23:09,440
 Asia, the 60% of emissions, that's where there should be much more activities.

220
00:23:09,440 --> 00:23:14,220
 So, I think, I'm sure that Europe is well off here, we can manage that.

221
00:23:14,220 --> 00:23:23,500
 But now, on the global side, there's too little R&D in emerging economies, actually, on energy, to cope with their questions there.

222
00:23:26,000 --> 00:23:36,340
 On other, let's say, even though this, let's say the money is there, and should be okay, but there's also some dark clouds in the horizon.

223
00:23:36,340 --> 00:23:38,660
 And it's really on the corporate funding.

224
00:23:38,660 --> 00:23:46,000
 We're seeing already the corporate R&D is starting to erode, because of the inflation, and because of the high interest rate.

225
00:23:46,200 --> 00:23:56,200
 And that's where the public sector institutions may need to give a push that the corporate funding in R&D stays good, because otherwise we won't get technologies on the market.

226
00:23:56,200 --> 00:24:01,480
 We may get a lot of research results and scientific papers, but we don't get the technologies on the market.

227
00:24:01,940 --> 00:24:10,780
 So, for upscaling, for instance, now, that is in risk, that there's not enough kind of funding to do the R&D for that side.

228
00:24:10,780 --> 00:24:23,220
 So, there's a range of challenges that the energy transition brings in technology-wise, and clear trends and challenges in the sense that, for instance, electricity, electric technologies will be very important.

229
00:24:23,220 --> 00:24:28,060
 Fuel is something that we need definitely in the future, but electricity will increase its role.

230
00:24:28,680 --> 00:24:31,320
 And when we speak about electric system, it's much more complex.

231
00:24:31,320 --> 00:24:39,640
 It's a very complex system, and in that sense, will need new skills, which skills necessarily would not be there.

232
00:24:39,640 --> 00:24:43,040
 We have been talking also very much in this conference about scaling up.

233
00:24:43,040 --> 00:24:48,420
 Scaling up is definitely the requirement for the energy transition.

234
00:24:48,420 --> 00:24:56,860
 You may have good technologies, but if they don't match the size and the scale of energy, it's in vain.

235
00:24:57,120 --> 00:25:01,020
 So, scaling up is something that we should keep definitely in mind.

236
00:25:01,020 --> 00:25:05,040
 And another important issue is also infrastructure.

237
00:25:05,040 --> 00:25:10,660
 If we don't have adequate infrastructure, but we have enough solar and wind, I mean, you can't use those.

238
00:25:10,660 --> 00:25:21,840
 So, infrastructures by large, even logistics and grids and so on, would be extremely important from the technology point of view as well.

239
00:25:23,420 --> 00:25:34,700
 Now, in order to understand slightly better the different challenges that we have with different technologies and the opportunities, let's just very quickly look how the energy system works and look at the energy framework.

240
00:25:34,700 --> 00:25:40,520
 I'm simplifying here very much, but basically, energy system is about demand and about supply.

241
00:25:40,520 --> 00:25:42,120
 That's an economy.

242
00:25:42,120 --> 00:25:44,080
 Economic terms in a way.

243
00:25:44,940 --> 00:25:52,780
 And your needs, our needs, they define the demand, and then we have the energy system, which is quite complex on the bottom here, will deliver you the supply.

244
00:25:52,780 --> 00:26:04,380
 So, your needs, our needs, the industrial needs, they define the demand, which is then supplied by the energy system, where we then get the CO2 emissions.

245
00:26:06,320 --> 00:26:09,860
 So, we're looking on the, on the, on the, on the gap between demand and supply.

246
00:26:09,860 --> 00:26:14,360
 So, we have the demand, which goes a single to the supply.

247
00:26:14,360 --> 00:26:19,640
 So, when we start to look on the supply system, it is, it has many stages.

248
00:26:19,640 --> 00:26:29,500
 There's a lot of conversion stages before the raw material energy turns into usable services that you need in, in your homes or in offices, in industries.

249
00:26:30,180 --> 00:26:35,540
 And these steps, these or these steps, have major, major, actually, losses.

250
00:26:35,540 --> 00:26:41,220
 So, much of the energy that we produce, actually, is lost.

251
00:26:41,220 --> 00:26:43,360
 And there's no use of that.

252
00:26:43,360 --> 00:26:49,880
 That's why energy efficiency, energy savings, in particular, close to the energy demand side, will be important.

253
00:26:49,880 --> 00:26:53,500
 Because what happens if I would be able to save in the demand?

254
00:26:53,500 --> 00:26:57,700
 The good things goes through the whole energy delivery chain.

255
00:26:58,280 --> 00:27:07,360
 It means I need less infrastructure, I need less cables, less transmission, less power plants, less fuels, less mining, less critical materials.

256
00:27:07,360 --> 00:27:09,840
 Everything is, is diminished.

257
00:27:09,840 --> 00:27:23,920
 So, so, if I would do my, my, my, my, my job on the energy demand side correctly, reduce the, the, the demand, as now the, the energy efficiency director will say, let's do it by 2050.

258
00:27:24,160 --> 00:27:27,580
 Each year, let's say half a percent improvement, at least.

259
00:27:27,580 --> 00:27:34,300
 We would actually say tens of percents in the supply, maybe in some countries up to 50%.

260
00:27:34,300 --> 00:27:39,680
 So, you need just half of the wind or solar to produce the same energy service that you need.

261
00:27:40,420 --> 00:27:44,840
 That's why I said before, the commission says energy efficiency first.

262
00:27:44,840 --> 00:27:54,560
 It's just cheapest energy, and it has the best benefits, and, and it has a lot of positive effects on the energy transition that we, that we have.

263
00:27:54,560 --> 00:28:00,060
 Energy transition without energy efficiency, I don't believe that it works.

264
00:28:00,180 --> 00:28:01,920
 I mean, we need so much materials.

265
00:28:01,920 --> 00:28:09,280
 Already now, when we look on, on the number, on the amount of copper, just for the cables, not just for the technology, just for the cables that we need.

266
00:28:09,280 --> 00:28:16,780
 That amounts the, the, the, the, the copper demand that we have had over the last 70 years.

267
00:28:16,780 --> 00:28:18,780
 So, so that's not enough.

268
00:28:19,200 --> 00:28:25,460
 So, that's why we need to be efficient as we are efficient with using money, let's be efficient in using, using, using energy.

269
00:28:25,460 --> 00:28:36,820
 And we have good example for many countries that, that this, this is, is, is manageable, though what is important to say, very often energy efficiency also incorporates, incorporates behavioral effects.

270
00:28:36,820 --> 00:28:38,500
 Behavior has to change.

271
00:28:38,500 --> 00:28:40,220
 It's not just a technology question.

272
00:28:42,980 --> 00:28:48,240
 So, so that's the energy demand side, and, and, and hopefully we can, as said, reduce there.

273
00:28:48,240 --> 00:28:51,080
 There's a lot of good technologies, as we have heard already today.

274
00:28:51,080 --> 00:28:55,700
 On that side, heat pumps, for instance, energy efficient appliances, you name it.

275
00:28:55,700 --> 00:28:57,760
 So, there's also technologies that can help us.

276
00:28:57,760 --> 00:29:06,680
 Now, moving to the supply side, the options that we have there are about the option for 2050, 50 are about those that we have.

277
00:29:06,680 --> 00:29:11,420
 There may come surprises that we have heard, and, and I have a few, few jokers here also.

278
00:29:12,180 --> 00:29:15,420
 But most likely, those technologies that you see here are what we have.

279
00:29:15,420 --> 00:29:17,480
 We have the traditional fossil fuels.

280
00:29:17,480 --> 00:29:24,220
 So, if we use fossil fuels in the future, we need to take the carbon, manage that, and, and store that, or reuse.

281
00:29:24,220 --> 00:29:28,560
 So, so, so, so carbon management and fossil fuels, that is a must in the future.

282
00:29:28,560 --> 00:29:38,920
 In case of bioenergy, which is also a combustion technology, produces CO2, we often say that, that bioenergy, well, the trees takes and plants the CO2 back.

283
00:29:38,920 --> 00:29:40,840
 So, we have a carbon circulation.

284
00:29:41,520 --> 00:29:51,980
 Now, depending on what kind of biomass you have, it may be the circulation takes 60 years, 70 years, like the Finnish forest, and, and most likely would need also, also carbon management for those type of biomasses.

285
00:29:51,980 --> 00:29:55,920
 If you have very quick growing crops, that would not be a problem.

286
00:29:55,920 --> 00:30:00,240
 So, so carbon capture and storage and utilization.

