00:30:00,760 --> 00:30:05,580
 That would be something that we need to look really definitely on, on technologies that emit CO2.

288
00:30:05,580 --> 00:30:09,300
 Being bioenergy, most likely, but in any way on fossil fuel.

289
00:30:09,300 --> 00:30:12,940
 Then we have a range of electric technologies, which are CO2-free.

290
00:30:12,940 --> 00:30:15,500
 Old renewables, like hydropower, we heard about that.

291
00:30:15,500 --> 00:30:16,480
 There's a lot of potential.

292
00:30:16,480 --> 00:30:18,560
 Air, air, of course, in the surroundings.

293
00:30:19,220 --> 00:30:23,660
 Then we have new renewables, mainly solar and wind, those are the two technologies that grow.

294
00:30:23,660 --> 00:30:27,860
 And then we have, of course, nuclear power, power, which is more traditional energy.

295
00:30:30,680 --> 00:30:32,480
 And now, let's look in the future.

296
00:30:32,480 --> 00:30:38,100
 This is what our friend, Mihail, he thought that it would be interesting to see.

297
00:30:38,100 --> 00:30:42,140
 Where could we go with electric products, supply technologies?

298
00:30:42,140 --> 00:30:45,580
 So let's say that research is successful.

299
00:30:45,580 --> 00:30:47,540
 Where could that bring?

300
00:30:47,980 --> 00:30:54,480
 So we have definitely an energy dream, which is a fusion power plants, which work with water.

301
00:30:54,480 --> 00:30:55,920
 I mean, this is not a joke.

302
00:30:55,920 --> 00:30:58,640
 Fusion power works with water.

303
00:30:58,640 --> 00:31:02,240
 One liter water is 300 liter equivalent oil.

304
00:31:02,240 --> 00:31:10,220
 And that's why in Hollywood films, actually, if you remember this DeLorean by Emmett Brown,

305
00:31:10,220 --> 00:31:13,400
 he was the, you know, the Back to the Future inventor.

306
00:31:13,400 --> 00:31:17,140
 He had fusion power in his car and used water for that.

307
00:31:17,520 --> 00:31:21,160
 It was not a joke in the sense that, yes, water has hydrogen.

308
00:31:21,160 --> 00:31:25,300
 And in hydrogen, we have two isotopes, which are important for fusion.

309
00:31:25,300 --> 00:31:28,840
 So let's take a short physics lesson in fusion.

310
00:31:28,840 --> 00:31:29,680
 How does it work?

311
00:31:29,680 --> 00:31:32,060
 I know economists hate physics.

312
00:31:32,060 --> 00:31:32,740
 I'm a physicist.

313
00:31:32,740 --> 00:31:33,700
 I know that.

314
00:31:33,700 --> 00:31:34,560
 They hate that.

315
00:31:34,560 --> 00:31:36,680
 But now, let's just concentrate.

316
00:31:36,680 --> 00:31:37,980
 And I think we managed it.

317
00:31:37,980 --> 00:31:46,640
 So, fusion is about very, very, let's say, the light is nuclear, which we have, which is hydrogen.

318
00:31:47,060 --> 00:31:48,660
 Hydrogen has three isotopes.

319
00:31:48,660 --> 00:31:50,840
 The ordinary hydrogen, they have a deuterium.

320
00:31:50,840 --> 00:31:51,940
 There's one neutron more.

321
00:31:51,940 --> 00:31:52,760
 That's too difficult.

322
00:31:52,760 --> 00:31:54,580
 But anyway, it's heavier.

323
00:31:54,580 --> 00:31:56,460
 And then we have tritium, which is more heavier.

324
00:31:56,460 --> 00:31:58,440
 Take the deuterium and tritium.

325
00:31:58,440 --> 00:31:59,900
 Let's put it together.

326
00:32:00,580 --> 00:32:02,420
 And then let's heat up it.

327
00:32:02,420 --> 00:32:05,600
 Now comes quite interesting.

328
00:32:05,600 --> 00:32:08,100
 We heat up to 100, 150 million degrees.

329
00:32:08,100 --> 00:32:11,360
 And that's a challenge because the sun is just 10 million.

330
00:32:11,360 --> 00:32:13,140
 So we go to 10 suns.

331
00:32:13,140 --> 00:32:13,900
 Heat up.

332
00:32:14,440 --> 00:32:19,000
 Then, of course, the atoms become ionized atoms, and everything is a plasma.

333
00:32:19,000 --> 00:32:20,600
 That's a plasma ball.

334
00:32:20,600 --> 00:32:22,660
 You have seen maybe in James Bond, you see the plasma.

335
00:32:22,660 --> 00:32:24,640
 And then you need to confine that.

336
00:32:24,640 --> 00:32:26,500
 Have a manganese or laser.

337
00:32:26,500 --> 00:32:28,280
 You see on the bottom some of the technologies.

338
00:32:28,280 --> 00:32:32,820
 And you confine it, make it very dense, and boom, then we have the fusion reaction.

339
00:32:32,820 --> 00:32:34,860
 And that causes a lot of energy.

340
00:32:34,860 --> 00:32:46,520
 And indeed, with just those two isotopes, which are in water, you really get a lot of energy out of the reaction.

341
00:32:47,620 --> 00:32:49,060
 Of course, this is very challenging.

342
00:32:49,060 --> 00:32:51,720
 I mean, keep in some way intact the plasma.

343
00:32:51,720 --> 00:32:55,180
 We will see in a while how challenging that is.

344
00:32:55,180 --> 00:33:02,840
 But the benefit with the fusion is that instead of the fission, which has a lot of radio toxicity for thousands of years,

345
00:33:02,840 --> 00:33:07,620
 the fusion, the radio toxicity, which comes from the neutron.

346
00:33:07,620 --> 00:33:14,500
 The neutron is the one which hits the wall of the fusion reactor, and it makes the walls slightly radioactive.

347
00:33:14,500 --> 00:33:16,220
 So we have to wait for 100 years.

348
00:33:16,340 --> 00:33:20,220
 100 years, then the radioactivity will have a decade away.

349
00:33:20,220 --> 00:33:21,920
 So no waste.

350
00:33:21,920 --> 00:33:29,360
 So what you have is water and a black box, and you get energy, and then you keep the waste for 100 years.

351
00:33:29,360 --> 00:33:32,800
 So it's the ideal final solution, I would say, for sure.

352
00:33:32,800 --> 00:33:38,420
 So now the question is that what do we need to do here in order to have the fusion working?

353
00:33:38,420 --> 00:33:43,380
 And that's where we need to really confine the plasma.

354
00:33:43,380 --> 00:33:45,080
 So first heat up it, confine.

355
00:33:45,480 --> 00:33:48,000
 And then, of course, you have to keep it there, time-wise.

356
00:33:48,000 --> 00:33:50,360
 I mean, if it just bombs is away, nothing happens.

357
00:33:50,360 --> 00:33:52,420
 So you have to keep it for a certain time.

358
00:33:52,420 --> 00:34:01,680
 And those three factors, density, temperature, and the confinement time, that is the critical so-called triple product, which needs to exceed a certain threshold level.

359
00:34:01,800 --> 00:34:10,500
 And here you see on the right-hand side where we are, we are not yet there, but with the ITER reactor, the European Initiative of Fusion, we are very close to that.

360
00:34:10,620 --> 00:34:12,000
 So it should demonstrate that.

361
00:34:12,000 --> 00:34:15,500
 So you see here the landmark experiment, the big ITER.

362
00:34:15,500 --> 00:34:17,780
 These are quite complicated devices.

363
00:34:17,780 --> 00:34:26,000
 ITER is a big magnet, which really keeps with manganess the plasma together and really compacts it.

364
00:34:26,000 --> 00:34:30,820
 And it should produce ten times more heat or energy than you put in.

365
00:34:30,820 --> 00:34:39,540
 Then we had the laser system, which is on the right-hand side, which the U.S. researchers have used.

366
00:34:39,540 --> 00:34:57,000
 And last December, there was a lot of news about fusion, that, yes, there's a breakthrough and lead in terms of the reaction, of the fusion reactor, reaction, which in this case is really handled in the way that we have a small pellet of deuterium and deuterium and two very powerful lasers that shoot on that.

367
00:34:57,000 --> 00:35:06,400
 And that cause really such a confinement temperature goes to 100, 150 million degrees, and you have very dense plasma, and the fusion reaction start.

368
00:35:06,780 --> 00:35:09,820
 They got 50% more energy than they put in the reaction.

369
00:35:09,820 --> 00:35:11,560
 Now there's a small caveat.

370
00:35:11,560 --> 00:35:14,620
 They forgot to tell that the lasers needed 100 times more energy.

371
00:35:14,620 --> 00:35:18,740
 So if you come for that, we are still a way of off.

372
00:35:18,740 --> 00:35:24,580
 But a breakthrough in terms of the fusion reaction, but not a breakthrough in technology.

373
00:35:24,580 --> 00:35:34,540
 And the breakthrough of the technology, that's something that we expect that will come to the experiments and most likely toward the end of this century.

374
00:35:34,540 --> 00:35:43,960
 That's the timeline where we expect that the commercial fusion reactors, working with water, so to say, would be there and useful.

375
00:35:43,960 --> 00:35:49,300
 An important maybe change in the fusion research.

376
00:35:49,300 --> 00:35:51,480
 Fusion research is really big science.

377
00:35:51,480 --> 00:35:55,200
 One experiment, 20 million euros, right.

378
00:35:55,640 --> 00:36:11,820
 And it's really expensive, and I think there's no change in the research in the sense that we expect that linking private industries more with the fusion research, may bring the scientists and the entrepreneurs who can make workable technologies together.

379
00:36:12,200 --> 00:36:24,680
 We've seen that in space, space industries, bringing SpaceX into NASA, made it possible to really create super technologies for spacecraft, reusing the rockets, et cetera.

380
00:36:24,680 --> 00:36:27,480
 The same thing should happen most likely in fusion.

